{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_kestrel_ver01/data/sn85060004/00516994757/1937111601/0510.xml":{"full_text":"el (VI A14)\n(o Y (e\nInternational News Dispatches\nAppear Exclusively in The Light\nVOL. LVII\u2014NO. 301.\nFIRST FROST FORECAST FOR A. SECTION\nARRESTED AFTER\nFATAL SHOT\nCLAUDE (\u201cCOWBOY\") HENRY BEHIND BARS\nHeld in pistol slaying of former S. A. policeman.\nGHINESE MOVE\nGAPITAL TO\nSAFETY\nNANKING, Nov. 15.\u2014(#)\u2014The\ngovernment decided tonight to move\nto Hankow, on the Yangtze nearly\n300 miles west, because of the thre\u2018\nto the capital by Japanese armies.\nBy The Assbciated Press. 1\\\nThree of China\u2019s great cities t.odayl\nlay in the path of Japan's army ad\nvancing from Shanghai. while the\nBrussels Far Eastern conference,\nfrustrated in its first peace attempt,\ntook a recess. y\nChinese fled Nanking, their cap\nftal; Tsinan, capital of the rich\nShantung province; and Soochow,\ncentral point in the Chinese de-|\nfenses between Shanghai and Nan\nking.\nChinese authorities actively dis\ncussed the advisability of main\ntaining the capital at Nanking, in\n_view of the Japanese advanee on the\n\"Chinese \u201cHindenburg\u201d line, some|\n125 miles to the southeast.\nPREDICT NANKING FALL\nForeign military observers pre\n_dicted Japan\u2019s fighters could reach\nNanking within a month.\nItaly was expected to bolt the\nBrussels conference when it recon\nvenes Monday and takes up the\nquestion of positive help for China.\nItaly voted \u201cno\u201d and Norway, Swed\nen and Denmark refrained from\nvoting yesterday on a declaration\ncriticizing Japan for her action in\nChina and her refusal to come to\nthe conference.\nA source close to the foreign of\nfice in Tokio said Japanese with\ndrawal from the nine-power pact\npledging respect for Chinese sov\nereignty, under which the Brussels\nassembly was called, would be con\nsidered within the next few days.\nDIPLOMATIC TALKS\nInsurgent headquarters at Irun,\nin warring Spain, announced Japan\nwould recognize Generalissimo Fran\ncisco Franco\u2019s insurgent governmeat\nNovember 25, anniversary of the\nsigning of the German-Japanese\nanti-communism pact which Italy\nrecently joined.\nElsewhere, international interest\ncentered on diplomatic talks Britain\narranged with Germany and Bel\ngium, which held possibility of far\nreaching effect.\nBritain sent Lord Halifax to Ger\nmany, probably to discuss Chancel\nlor Hitler\u2019s often-expressed colonial\nambitions. At the same time she!\nwelcomed King Leopold of Belgium,\nwho came to seal the friendship of\nhis tiny kingdom and the British|\nempyre. l\nPublished by The Light Publishing Company\nv San Antonio, Texas\nFormer Policeman Dies in Inn Shooting\nARTHUR SINCLAIR\nEx-policeman slain.\n11 Meet Death\n'InCrash\nBRUSSELS, Nov. 16.\u2014(INS)\u2014A\nprince of the former German royal\nhouse of Hesse, his son and three\ndaughters were among those killed\nwhen a Vienna-London passenger\nPplane crashed in flames with a loss\nof 11 lives at Ostend today, accord\ning to reports here,\nThere was no immediate identifi\ncation of the reported royal vica\ntims,\n_\u2014\u2014\nHunters Must Stay\nOff Reservation\nHunters near Leon Springs may\nfind themselves slightly off the\nreservation by getting on the res\nervation, army officials indicated\nTuesday.\nLeon Springs Military reservation\nhas been declared a federal game\npreserve, and no hunting will be\npermitted there this year. The en\ntire reservation will be patrolled by\\\n12 deputy game gardens in uniform,\nwith authority to enforce the regu-\u2018\nlations.\nIn prior years hunters have found\nthe reservation an attractive spot\nto hunt.\n\nMarie of Rumania\nSuffers Relapse\nBUCHAREST. Nov. 16.\u2014(INS)\u2014\nDowager Queen Marie of Rumania,\nseriously ill for several weeks suf\nfered a relapse today due to a nev\u2018\nhemorrhage.\nBoys Keeping House\nAs Mother Stlulies|\nNEW YORK, Nov. 16.\u2014(\u00ae\u2014Mrs.\nIsabel Urbach, who is attending col\nlege while her two sons do the\nhousekeeping, said today her ex\npeiience proved that boys can be\nas helpful as girls around the home.\nHer sons, Bertram, 14, and\nGeorge, 12, do the cooking. wash\nthe dishes, make the bed and sew\non their own buttons while she\nstudies at Hunter college 10 be\nTHE_ 4T\u00a77i7LIGHT\nE AN 11\nEA(INDEPENDEN i~ SR EXAST B WSPAPER I\nFIVE 3HOTS\nTERRORIZE\nCROWD\nArthur Sinclair Is Victim;\nClaude Henry Held\nAfter Quarrel.\nShot down with his own pistol in\nthe hand of an erstwhile friend, Ar\nthur Sinclair, 38, ex-San Antonio\npoliceman, was fatally wounded\nearly Tuesday at the Monte Carlo\ninn, 1620 Nogalitos street.\nClaude (\u201cCowboy\u201d) Henry, 24,\nformer Brackenridge High school\nathlete and prize fighter, was be\ning held by police in connection\nwith the slaying.\nA verdict of murder was return\ned at the inquest into the ex-po\nliceman\u2019s death.\nJ. P. Palmer, special deputy con- 4\nstable on duty at the inn, reported\nthat Henry fired his last shot as\nSinclair, already twice wounded,\nstaggered through the rear doorway\nof the tavern. Then, Palmer said,\nHenry clubbed the dying man on\nthe head with the pistol.\nINN CROWDED.\nThe shooting occurred at 12:15\na. m, at a time when the Monte\nCarlo inn was crowded with diners\nand dancers. A mechanical piano\nwas grinding out a swing tune.\nHenry told police Sinclair, who\nresigned from the police force May\n12, 1937, to become a special of\nficer, first fired two shots at him,\nand that he took the gun away\nfrom him and shot in self-defense.\nM. T. (\u201cLone Wolf\u201d) Gonzaullas,\nfirearms expert of the state depart\nment of public safety, was to arrive\nin San Antonio Tuesday afternoon\nto make paraffin tests to determine\nwhether there are powder marks on\nSinclair\u2019's hands. If they are found\n-|it will bear out Henry's contention\nthat Sinclair also fired the weapon.\nThe fatal shooting apparently\nclimaxed a dispute between the\npair over remarks addressed by\nSinclair to two young women the\nmen had met in the night club a\n'(ew minutes before.\nSHOTS HEARD.\nHenry told police that he and\nSinclair left the Crystal bar on\nWest Commerce street in the ex\nofficer\u2019s automobile and drove to\nthe Monte Cario inn. There they\nsat down at a table occupied by\nThelma Hay Condra, 2918 South\nFlores street, and Mary Coy, 1130\nWest Mulberry avenue.\nShortly before 12:15 a. m., Sin\nclair arose and went through the\nrear door \u2019o the parking lot. Henry\nfollewed. Ten minutes later two\nshots sounded. After a brief in\nterval, there came three more.\nThe final shot came as the former\npoliceman staggered back through\nthe doorway and collapsed on the\nfloor, from whence he twice tried\nvainly to rise. Henry, a 45 caliber\nfrontier model revolver in his hand,\nhad followed Sinclair to the inn.\nPalmer said he demanded that\nHenry surrender the weapon, but he\nrefused to do so until given a glass\nof beer. When police officers ar\nrived on the scene he informed them\nhe was frightened and asked to be\ntaken from the place.\nGIRL'S STATEMENT.\ni Miss Condra, in a written state\nment, told investigating officers that\nshe and Miss Coy were seated at a\n\u2018table when Sinclair, Henry and a\nthird man, whose name is not\nknown, entered and sat down with\nthem.\n\u201cMr. 8inclair asked us to have\nsome beer or liquor with him,\u201d she\nsaid, \u201cbut we refused. Then he\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014e e\n(Continued on Page 12, Col. 3.\nS T\ncome a chemistry teacher.\n\u201cThere is no reason why this\njcar't be worked out in other\nhomes,\u201d Mrs. Urbach said. \u201cIt; a\nmatter of having the necessity for\n|it, and then the children adapt\nthemselves to it. I get more from|\nms boys than many women do from\ntheir girls.\u00bb\nl The boys. Incidentally, are proud\nof iaeir ability to keep house.\nMember of the Associated Press A Constructive Force in the Community\nTUESDAY, NOVEMBER 16, 1937.\nA, A oy e\nESCAPED\nJOHN OLEY\nSought in prison break.\nPlanes Search for\nRebels\ni\nJERUSALEM, Nov. 16.\u2014\u00ae\u2014A\nsquaaron of airplanes and thiee\ncompanies of British infantry\nsearched the Safed hills today for\na band of Arab rebels who were\nengaged in a gkirmish with govern\nmeni forces. Three of the rebels\u2018\n\u2018were killed in the fighting last\nnighit.\nMarked Ballots\nReach City Hall\nS T\nThe city hall Tuesday had a stock\nof marked sample ballots favoring\nthe proposed 5-cent ad tax, to be\nvoted upon by San Antonians at a\nspecial election November 23.\nPrinted at the bottom of each\nballot was the following:\n\u201cSponsored by the San Antonio\nAdvertising club and endorsed by\n20 other leading civic, commercial\nand labor organizations.\u201d\nThe ballots first appeared in the\nrecreation department, but workers\nthere professed ignorance as to\ntheir source. Administration leaders\ndenied that city employes had been\nordered to distribute them.\n\u2014_\u2014\nThief Cuts Screen,\nEscapes With $53\nTheft of $53.55 from a drawer in\nhis home was reported by A. Garza\nof 504 South Pecos street to police\nTuesday. He said a screen in a side\nwindow was cut and entrance made\nthrough it.\nA\nThe Weather\nSan Antonio and vicinity: 'Fair|:\nand colder Tuesday night, probably|\nfrost in hill sections; Wednesday|'\nfair with slowly rising temperatures.\nModerate northerly winds.\nHighest temperature Tuesday,|:\nabout 60 degrees; lowest tempera-|\nture Wednesday morning, about 36\ndegrees; highest temperature Wed\nnesday, about 66 degrees; highest\ntemperature Monday, 80 degrees;\nlowest temperature Tuesday morn\ning, 45 degrees.\nEast Texas (east one-hundredth\n|meridian) Fair and colder in east\nand south portions, frost nearly to\nthe coast except in the Rio Grande\nvalley if wind subsides, freezing in\nthe \u00abnorth and interior of extreme\neast portion Tuesday night; Wed\n{nesday fair with slowly rising tem\nperature. Fresh to strong northerly\nwinds on coast, diminishing Wed\nnesday.\nWest Texas (west one-hundredth\nmeridian) Fair, slightly colder in\nextreme southeast portion, not quite\n|so cold in the northwest portion,\nprobably frost in south portion|\nTuesday night; Wednesday, partly\ncloudy with rising temperature.\nTEMPERATURES.\nMONDAY\u2014 Zam .......54]\n3pm.......T% 3am.......51\n4pm .......80 4am .......49|]\n5p. M 4e0eee.78 Sam .......47\n6 p. ceecee.T8 6 a m .......46]\n7P }.......74 Tam,......45\nSp. M .e.....72 Sa m .......47|\n%p.m .......70 9%a m ,......49]\n109p m .......57 10 a. m........50],\n11 p. m. E a m........ssg\n%UMBSDAY\u2014 1 p m.o. .57\ntam .57 2p m... .59\nWind. at 12:30 p. m., 16 miles per\n\u2018hour from the northeast. Humidity, at\n6:34 a m.. 53 per cent- mean for No\nvember, %0 per cent: at 12:34 p. m..\n44 per cent: mean. 33. l\n(Additional Weather on Page 2.)\n3 KIDNAPERS\nFSCAPE\nL\nConvicted Trio Tie Up Five\nand Abduct Sixth Guard\nin Armed Break.\nJAMESVILLE, N. Y, Nov. 16.\u2014(#\nThree men convicted of kidnaping\nJohn J. O'Connell Jr., of Albany,\nescaped at about 1:45 a. m. today\nfrom the Onondaga county jail here\nafter binding and gagging four\nkeepers, a matron and kidnaping\nanother keeper.\nThe prisoners were Percy Geary\nand John Oley of Albany, sentenced\n\u2018to 77 years, and Harold Crowley of\nNew York City, given 28 years.\nH. H. Paddock, superintendent of\nthe prison. said the three were arm\ned with two guns. He added that\nbars of one of the prisoners\u2019 cells\nwere sawed and then placed togeth\ner with chewing gum to avoid de-|\ntection.\nTIE UP KEEPERS 1\nWhen John Corbett, a keeper, en\ntered the cell block one prisoner\npounced on him, bound him and\ntook his keys. The prisoner then lib\nerated the other two, and the trio\nwent to the guard room, Paddock\nsaid.\nThere they encountered Keepers\nLeroy Pease, Earl Brown and Fran\ncis Crowley. They bound and gagged\nthese keepers with sheets and were\nready to leave when Mrs. Nellie\nHills, a matron, entered, Paddock\nsaid.\nMrs. Hills was also bound.\nKIDNAP KEEPER\nIn the prison yards the convicts\nencountered Keeper Edward Hayes,\nwho was reporting for work. They\nforced Hayes to the latter\u2019s auto\nmobile. took his k-ys and bo\u2018gnd\nhim. They then sped away with\nHayes In the back seat to Syracuse,\nfive miles away.\nThere they released Hayes un\nharmed. Paddock quoted Hayes as\nsaying the three transferred to an\nother car which he was unable to\ndescribe.\nOley, Geary and Crowley were\namong eight convicted of the O'Con\nnell kidnaping in Federal court in\nBinghamton, N. Y., on August 12.\nIn addition to the prison terms, each\nwas fined $10,000.\nThe sentences were to be served|\nat Alcatraz, but appeals delayed\ntheir removal.\nLOS ANGELES. Nov. 16.\u2014\u00ae\u2014\nJames Sweeney, last of 13 suspects\narrested for the kidnaping of John\nJ. O\u2019'Connell Jr., was released from\nLos Angeles county jail to federal\nofficers last Saturday for return to\nUtica.\nSweeney, using the name of James\nSaunders, was conducting an auto\nmobile business here when arrested.\nAfter admitting his identity, he\nwaived extradition.\nAttention of police was directed to\nSweeney when it was reported his\nbusiness losses exceeded $20,000 last\nyear, but he continued to live luxur\niously.\nFederal authorities here indicated\nthey were trying to locate, through\nSweeney, the $40,000 ransom re\nported paid for O'Connell\u2019s return to\nhis prominent up-state New York\nfamily.\n\nBelgian K}ng on\nVisit to London\nLONDON, Nov. 16.\u2014(/P\u2014Leopold,\nking of the Belgians, arrived at\nflag-draped Victoria station today\non a state visit to England.\nKing George, resplendent in the\ncrimson tunic of a field marshal,\nsnapped to a salute and shook hands\nwith Leopold as the young visiting\nmonarch stepped from his train to a\nplatform carpeted with scarlet plush_\nA hour before Leopold\u2019s ar\ufb02v%\nViscount Halifax left for Berlin\nconfer 'vith Chancellor Adolf Hitler\non matters of importance to British-\nGerman relations.\n\u2014_\u2014\nTRAINS CRASH HEAD-ON.\nCREWE, Eng.. Nov. 16.\u2014\u00ae\u2014Fif\nteen persons were slightly injurgd\ntoday when the Scotland-to-London\nnight express ran into the rear of\nlthe crack train, Night Scot, outside\nCrewe station.\nTWENTY-TWO PAGES\nBusiness Retarded by\nIntolerable Taxes\nThe business recession has reached the point\nwhere it alarms the nation.\nIt is evident that it also alarms the adminis\ntration.\nThere is one all-inclusive reason for the pres\nent business recession and for the impending\nthreat of another black depression, and that is\nthe administration\u2019s mistaken philosophy of reg\nimentation; its meddling with business, hamper\ning business, hindering it, harassing it and\nruthlessly rifling its pockets of gains that should\nbe used to expand business and provide jobs for\nthe jobless.\nOne of the chief causes of business fear is the\nintolerable tax situation.\nThis nation, at peace, is taxed more heavily\nthan other, war-like nations are taxed for war.\nBusiness can not carry that impossible burden\nand go forward; individual initiative, which is\nthe thing that makes business advance when it\ndoes advance, can not function under a handicap\nSO oppressive.\nPresident Roosevelt appreciates the dangers\nof this unbearable situation and is calling in\npractical men to help find a way out of it.\nLet us hope that among its FIRST expedients\nthe administration will act, at the special session\nof congress, to eliminate the capital gains tax, or\nelse to revise it so that investing capitdl can go into\nthe expansion of industry, the promotion of trade\nand the increase of employment. There is no capi\ntal gains tax in England, and England is the ONE\ncountry today where money is being spent to make\nbusil?ess busier and put more men and women to\nwork.\nLet us hope the excess profits tax also will be\nrevised, so that it will become possible again for\nbusiness to make use of profits to build necessary\nreserves and to finance honest expansion.\nThat ALSO would make business better and\nprovide jobs for the jobless.\nTo stop the business slump and start the\ncountry on the way back to prosperity it will be\nnecessary for government to stop extorting the\npeople\u2019s money from useful enterprise and wast\ning it on hordes, and constantly increasing\nhordes, of worthless, useless, non-productive\npoliticians.\nWe must end the conflict of labor with labor,\nwhich sacrifices the best interests of the actual\nworkers in order that a few labor racketeers may\ngain illegitimate wealth, and a few demagogues\nsecure political power.\nThere must be an end to the ruinous process\nof taxing the thrifty, resourceful, enterprising,\nemploying, wealth-creating class of the commu\n7 (Continued on Page 6, Col. 1)\nHOODED NIEN\n|NVADE GLUB\nS\nMIAMI, Fla. Nov. ll.\u2014lINS)\u2014-'\nOne hundred and fifty hooded mem-\nbers of the Ku Klux Klan staged a|\nraid on the La Paloma, night club|\non the outskirts of Miami, early to\nday, smashed furnishings of the|\nclub, routed patrons, waiters, bar\ntenders from the building and or\ndered the management not to re\nopen the place.\nOne waiter who refused to vacate\nthe club on orders of the fully\nrobed group was dragged from the\nbuilding by the raiders and severely\nbeaten.\nPolice and sheriff\u2019s offices, how\never, said they had received no re\nport of the incident early this morn\ning.\nAl Youst, proprietor of the club,\nwas absent when the incursion was\nstaged. He declared the place would\nbe re-furnished today, and would be\nre-opened tonight in defiance of the\n'Klan's order to remain closed.\nYoust said he would seek police\nprotection to prevent another such|\nraid by the hooded group. i\ne ey\nP in the city and wvicinity.\nFDR Bothered by\nBad Tooth\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 16.=-(P\u2014\nPresident Roosevelt cancelled all his\nengagements todav because of a\npainfully infected tooth while Vice\nPresident Garner was having one\npulled.\nThe vice president went back to\nwork immediately after a trip to the\ndentist\u2019s.\nMr. Roosevelt\u2019s trouble was more\u2018\nserious. It developed last night\nafter dinner and capsed the presi\ndent to lose considerable sleep.\n\u2014_\u2014 e\nBootleg Collieries\nat Mines Checked\nHARRISBURG, Pa., Nov. 16.\u2014UP)\nA check of all bootleg collieries in\nPennsylvania\u2019s anthracite fields is\nunder way to learn the extent of\nany \u201cbig time racketeering,~ Secre\ntary of Mines Michae]l J. Hartneady\ndisciosed today.\nFacketeers who hauled liquor and\nbeer into Pennsylvania during pro\nhibition are reported building wash\neries in the hills to clean coal.\nEDITION\nJARBOE SEES\n36-DEGREE\nWEATHER\nHERE\n'Snow Falls in Half Dozen\n1 Northern Cities; Cool\nWave to Be Short.\nSan Antonio will get its first\ntaste of winter early Wednesday,\nwhen the mercury will sink to\naround 36 degrees,\nU. 8. Forecaster J. H. Jarboe\nwarned that frost was probable in\nthe hill sections around San An\ntonio during the early hours of\nWednesday.\nThe cool wave, however, will be\nof short duration, the observer said.\nSlowly rising temperatures will be\nin evidence Wednesday afternoon,\nand with diminishing winds Thurs\nday morning should not be nearly\nso cold.\n22-MILE WIND.\nBorne on a 22-mile-an-hour wind,\nSan Antonio awoke Tuesday morn\ning to find a genuine norther\npounding at its door. From a high\nof 80 degrees Monday afternoon,\nthe temperature slipped to 45 de\ngrees at 7 a. m. Tuesday, lowest of\nthe season.\nAlthough the sun was shining,\nthe wind was expected to keep the\nmercury down to around 60 de\ngrees in the afternoon, 20 points\nbelow Monday\u2019s high.\nSNOW IN NORTH.\nDespite the chill blasts, San An\ntonians had much to be thankful\nfor.\nSnow was falling Tuesday in half\na dozen cities, extending as far\nsouth as St. Louis and Oklahoma\nCity. In Omaha, which also had\nsnow, the temperature dipped to 22\ndegrees. Huron, S. D., was the\ncoldest spot in the United States,\nreporting a low of 14,\nDelayed Winter\nStrikes Texas.\nBy The Associated Press.\nTexas had a red nose today from\na straight punch delivered by a\n'long-delayed winter that apparently\nhad come to set up quarters for\niseveral months.\nMeteorologists scanned a weath=\ner map, noted the 19-degree reading\nat Pampa, traces of snow deep in\nthe Panhandle, killing frost down\non the south plains and even a drop\ndown in the Rio Grande Valley, and\ndecided winter had come,\nLow readings of 24 at Amarillo,\nPlainview and Lubbock, with heavy,\nkilling frost accompanying, were\n|reported. Frost was expected to\nfacilitate cotton picking in the Lub\nbock sector, which now indicates\n800,000 bales for 17 counties of the\nSou.h Plains regfon for a new high\nrecord. Frost topped out plants and\ncaused shedding.\nFrom Borger came a report of 29\ndegrees while Vernon had nippy 33\ndegree weather and Wichita Falls\nIshivered at 30 degrees. San Angelo\n'and Big Spring reported a similar\n(readings of 38, but no rain or snow.\nOther readings included Palestine,\n41; Sherman, 36 with rainfall;\nGainesville, 335 with light rain and\n|a bit of sleet; Denison, 35 with rain\n|and hail; Paris, 36 and overcast\nskies; Port Worth and Dallas, 37\nwith overcast skies; Corsicana, 40.\nE?Gulf Coast Storm\nWarning Posted\nNEW ORLEANS, Nov. 16\u2014@#\u2014\nNorthwest storm warnings were\nordered today by the United States\n|weather bureau here from Bay St.\n'|Louis, Miss., to Carrabelle, Fla. The\n{bureau said a disturbance central\nInear the Mississippi coast was mov\n|ing eastward.\nA similar warning was issued last\n'Inight for the West Gulf coast from\nNew Orleans to Brownsville, Texas.\n||'The warning said there would be\nrbhmh to strong northerly winds on\nithe Texas coast last nigh$ and on\nlmmmmn","height":"21136","width":"16696"}}
